The results of the present analysis indicate, from 1969 to 1987, a sharp and 
stable decline in cardiovascular (CVD) mortality in Italians aged 35-74 years 
(37.6% in males 53.6% in females). These trends were responsible for consistent 
reductions of total mortality (27.5% and 38% in the two gender groups, 
respectively), and for the increase of life expectancy. The decrease involved 
the two major components of CVD mortality, i.e. coronary heart disease (CHD) 
(23% in males and 44% in females) and cerebrovascular diseases (Stroke) (42.6% 
